---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;
---

<Layout
  title={`Agent Product Design — ${config.site.title}`}
  description="How to design AI agent products: model reasoning, tools, memory, workflows, permissions, governance, and human-in-the-loop patterns."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main pageTitle="Agent Product Design" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Agent products are not just chatbots. They combine model reasoning, tools,
      memory, workflows, permissions, and governance.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Agent Is Not Just Chat</h2>
    <p>
      The word "agent" gets used loosely. A chatbot that answers questions is
      not an agent. An agent perceives context, reasons about goals, selects and
      uses tools, takes actions, and handles failures. The product design
      challenge is orchestrating all of these components into a reliable user
      experience.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      Agent = Model + Tools + Memory + Workflow + Governance
    </h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Model</strong> — The reasoning engine. What model, what temperature,
        what context window? The model choice affects reliability, latency, and cost.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tools</strong> — What can the agent read and write? APIs, databases,
        file systems, external services. Every tool is a capability and a risk.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Memory</strong> — Short-term (conversation context) and long-term
        (learned preferences, knowledge base). Memory determines whether the agent
        gets smarter or forgets.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Workflow</strong> — The orchestration logic. Multi-step reasoning,
        planning, execution order, error recovery, and retry strategies.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Governance</strong> — Permissions, audit logs, human approval gates,
        rate limits, and compliance rules. Without governance, agents are a liability.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Design Questions</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>What can the agent read?</li>
      <li>What can the agent do?</li>
      <li>When does it ask for approval?</li>
      <li>How does it recover from failure?</li>
      <li>What is logged and audited?</li>
      <li>What's the blast radius if the agent makes a wrong decision?</li>
      <li>How does the user correct or override the agent?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        Over-scoping the agent — giving it too many tools and too much autonomy
        before proving reliability.
      </li>
      <li>
        No clear failure recovery — if the agent fails mid-task, what does the
        user see? How does the system get back to a clean state?
      </li>
      <li>
        Treating HITL as an afterthought — human-in-the-loop is a core product
        flow, not a safety net you bolt on later.
      </li>
      <li>
        Ignoring governance — audit trails, permission boundaries, and approval
        workflows are not optional in enterprise contexts.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">How I Approach This</h2>
    <p>
      I start with the ontology: what entities exist, what relationships matter,
      what actions are possible. Then I define tool permissions and HITL
      checkpoints. The model and workflow come last — they're implementation
      details once the product structure is clear.
    </p>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/prompt-to-ontology")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Prompt-to-Ontology
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/ai-native-prd")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          AI-Native PRD
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "projects/prompt-to-ontology")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Prompt-to-Ontology Project
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
